CHAPTER VII

NEWNESS OF LIFE

WE see evidence in various times and places of something that seems quite new entering into human history—a new idea, a new art, a new invention—making a fresh starting—point for human activity. It is the same with what we call animal life and vegetable life; every new species must have had its starting-point. Life is always new. In a sense this is the commonest of truismS, for every individual organism is different from every other; but it is also true that the momentum of every fresh starting-point is always pulsing on, rising, gathering force, spreading itself like waves that pass the movement on through water until some larger wave, as it were accidentally, seems to have sufficient power to break down some barrier that till then had been impregnable. The accident is only apparent ; the force was there and growing all the time3 and if the water, after the apparent accident, rushes into some hollow of the shore, making an inland sea that never again recedes, it is not because there was a new force. Yet the inland sea is new.
